A field epidemiologist embedded in a state department of health runs the routine disease surveillance workflow for a panel of reportable conditions, processing dozens of new case reports each week from clinical labs and clinicians and triaging which ones warrant follow-up investigation. The current spreadsheet-based system loses cases in inboxes and makes it hard to spot week-over-week trends. Build an operational workflow app that takes each new report — date of onset, county, age, sex, race, occupation if relevant, exposure history, lab confirmation status — and routes it into the standing line list for that condition. The app should compute weekly counts and incidence rates relative to historical baselines, flagging conditions exceeding their threshold so the epidemiologist knows when to open an outbreak investigation. For each open investigation it should support both cohort study design and case-control study design follow-up depending on how the cluster was identified, with structured fields for the case definition, the analytic plan, candidate measures of association, and notes on confounding and effect modification. Cross-sectional studies of prevalence among populations of interest — long-term care facility residents, schoolchildren in a district, a workplace — should be supported as a separate workflow with their own questionnaire builder. The app should produce the weekly surveillance bulletin the epidemiologist distributes internally, pulling in updated line lists, status of open investigations, and a short narrative section the epidemiologist drafts. It should also support handoff: when an investigation closes, all its artifacts are preserved for the program's institutional memory and indexed so a future investigator working a similar cluster can find the prior work quickly.